<!-- HERITAGE -->
<section class="heritage">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="heritage-grid">
      <div class="heritage-content">
        <div class="section-label">Our Tradition</div>
        <h2>Under the banner of the <em>Irish Constitution</em></h2>
        <p>Sharman Crawford Lodge No. 608 operates under the Provincial Grand Lodge of Southern Cape, within the oldest and most democratic of the great Masonic constitutions — the Grand Lodge of Ireland.</p>
        <p>The Irish Constitution is known for its warmth, its inclusivity, and its enduring commitment to the universality of Masonic brotherhood. We are proud to carry that tradition to the southern tip of Africa.</p>
        <p>We are named for William Sharman Crawford — Irish reformer, champion of tenant rights, and a man of principle ahead of his time. His values of fairness, dignity, and courage for the right course shape our lodge culture to this day.</p>

        <div class="harari-quote" style="margin-top:2rem; border-left-color: var(--irish-green-light);">
          <blockquote style="font-size:1.1rem;">During Apartheid in South Africa, there was only one organisation permitted to fraternise across the colour line — and that organisation was Freemasonry.</blockquote>
          <cite>— Lodge de Goede Hoop, Cape Town</cite>
        </div>

        <p style="margin-top:1.4rem;">At a time when an entire nation was organised around the separation of people by race, the Lodge de Goede Hoop — the very temple where we meet today — was the only place in South Africa where men of all racial backgrounds could sit together as equals. This was not a quiet accommodation. It was a deliberate, principled stand. The Grand Lodge of South Africa, led by the courage of men like R.W. Brother Morris Levin, formally negotiated the right to admit men of colour as full members, with some rising to the highest offices within the Grand Lodge — at a time when such equality was illegal almost everywhere else in the country.</p>
        <p>When we walk through the doors of Lodge de Goede Hoop today, we walk into a building that chose the right side of history, quietly, before it was popular or safe to do so. That is a legacy worth knowing. And worth continuing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="heritage-badges">
        <div class="badge">
          <div class="badge-dot"></div>
          <div>
            <strong>Grand Lodge of Ireland</strong>
            <p>The oldest Grand Lodge operating under an unbroken charter — and a tradition of genuine fraternity across borders and backgrounds.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="badge">
          <div class="badge-dot"></div>
          <div>
            <strong>Provincial Grand Lodge — Southern Cape</strong>
            <p>Our provincial authority, linking us to a proud network of Irish Constitution lodges across southern Africa.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="badge">
          <div class="badge-dot"></div>
          <div>
            <strong>Lodge de Goede Hoop — Built 1803</strong>
            <p>A national monument. During Apartheid, it stood as the only formal space in South Africa where men of all races were permitted to meet as equals. That legacy lives in every stone of the building.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="badge">
